<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[192,1441,571,632]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,316,571,597]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
There are two somewhat spheroid, broadly connected, testaceous maculae in the center of the elytra. This characteristic will distinguish the members of this species from congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="14" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[191,1441,648,915]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,363,648,674]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Redescription.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[370,420,649,675]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Size:</emphasis>
Length 15.0 mm; width 4.0 mm. 
<emphasis box="[798,857,649,674]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Form</emphasis>
. As in 
<figureCitation box="[937,1016,648,674]" captionStart="Figures 78–81" captionStartId="60.[192,279,1859,1885]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-40@60.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="Figures 78–81. Habitus of Axina species. 78) Axina diversesignata. 79) A. lobispinula. 80) A. orcastomata. 81) A. plagiata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565011/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis box="[1026,1087,648,674]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Color</emphasis>
. Forebody, antennae, pterothorax black; elytra bicolorous, mostly black, with 2 somewhat spheroid, broadly connected, testaceous maculae in center of disc, apical 1/5 testaceous; legs bicolorous, femora and tibiae black, tarsi brown; abdomen bicolorous, visible basal 3 sternites black, visible distal apical 3 sternites yellow. 
<emphasis box="[953,1011,751,777]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Head</emphasis>
. Cranium finely punctate, frons about as wide as length of antennal pedicel; EW/FW 65/15. 
<emphasis box="[811,889,786,812]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum finely punctate, with 2 tumescences, concave at middle; PW/PL 150/205; elytra, asetiferous punctures striate, punctures extend slightly beyond elytron middle, width of interstitial spaces variable; EL/EW 600/130. 
<emphasis box="[896,1002,854,880]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1142,1225,854,881]" captionStart="Figures 40–43" captionStartId="50.[192,279,978,1004]" captionTargetBox="[320,1271,213,948]" captionTargetId="figure-11@50.[320,1271,213,948]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="Figures 40–43. Aedeagi. 40) Axina diversesignata. 41) A. orcastomata. 42) A. plagiata. 43) A. adelosa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564985/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
), phallobasic lobes slightly curvate apically; phallic plates not serrate; phallobasic apodeme abbreviated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[192,1440,931,991]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,310,931,957]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Variation.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[316,359,932,958]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Size</emphasis>
. Length 10.5–15.0 mm; width 2.2–4.0 mm. The centrally located elytral maculae vary slightly in shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[192,1442,1008,1069]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,378,1008,1034]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Natural history.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[711,789,1008,1034]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
during November, December, and March, in 
<collectingCountry box="[1306,1358,1008,1034]" name="Peru" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Peru</collectingCountry>
during May, and in 
<collectingCountry box="[331,396,1042,1068]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Brazil</collectingCountry>
during March and November.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
